Architecture Notes — load-bearing, do not touch without reading

Coordinate Pipeline
  screenToDocument / documentToScreen / quadVertexShaderWithTransform
  must stay in sync at all times. Any change to one requires retest of
  all three on physical iPad. Source of Phase 1's major bugs; must not
  regress.

  Canvas texture: 4096×4096 (sized from view.drawableSize, not
    view.bounds.size).
  fitSize model: max(viewport.w, viewport.h) — fill, not fit.
  Rotation convention: shader Y-up (visual CCW), Swift R(-θ) for
    Y-down equivalent.
  Marquee selection: stored as 4-point screen-space polygon mapped to
    doc space via screenToDocument. Routes through lasso pipeline.
    activeSelection is nil for all marquee selections — selectionPath
    is ground truth.

Pressure → Render Pipeline
  Apple Pencil firmware can return NaN force samples; the pressure
  path is NaN-guarded at four points (computePressure, touchesMoved
  interpolation, renderStroke per-point, shader clamp). Apple GPU
  point sprites cap at ~511 px; the brush vertex shader clamps
  out.pointSize to [0, 511] as the universal guarantee. Don't remove
  these guards without redoing the analysis in the Investigations
  Reference below.

Composite Sampling
  CanvasRenderer.compositeLayersToTexture(layers:) renders all visible
  layers over an opaque white background and returns the resulting
  MTL texture. Output has alpha = 1.0 and straight RGB equal to what's
  on screen. Used by Export to Photos (via compositeLayersToImage)
  and the eyedropper. One full 4096×4096 pass per call; only fired on
  user action, not per frame.

Memory
  4096×4096 × 4 bytes = 64 MB per layer.
  5 layers = 320 MB — monitor on base iPad, fine on iPad Pro.
  HistoryManager caps at 50 snapshots; each snapshot is 64 MB; the
  effective limit is the memory ceiling, not the count.

Worker Auth
  No auth, no rate limiting, CORS wide open — acceptable for
  TestFlight, must address before public launch.
  API key lives in Cloudflare Worker env var OPENAI_API_KEY.
  Deploy via `wrangler deploy` from cloudflare-worker/ with
  CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN set.


Investigations Reference

Pencil "stroke vanishes mid-stroke under heavy pressure" — two causes
(both addressed Apr 16):
  (1) NaN propagation. Swift's max(0, NaN) returns NaN, not 0. A
      single NaN force sample taints the stroke via interpolation
      (previousPressure ?? samplePressure) → all subsequent stamps
      have NaN pressure → Metal silently skips them.
  (2) Metal point sprite cap (~511 px on Apple A-series; M-series may
      be higher). renderStrokePreview multiplies by textureToScreen
      (~1.33) and zoomScale, so brush 200 + zoom 2 = 532, past the
      cap → silent fail.
  Both cause "stroke vanishes mid-stroke" depending on which trips
  first. Affects all tools because brush/eraser/line/rect/circle all
  route through the same pressure → point sprite path.

"Large brush size breaks the whole thing" — three causes (Apr 16):
  (1) BIG ONE: lastPoint updated every coalesced sample regardless of
      whether a stamp committed. At brush 200 + spacing 0.1, the
      threshold is 20 doc px, but Pencil samples land ~2 doc px apart
      → distance never accumulated past 20 → no stamps fired → stroke
      contains exactly one stamp until lift.
  (2) Preview pointSize cap exceedance — see above.
  (3) Fragment shader cost is O(size²); 200 px stamp = 40,000
      fragments per stamp at 240 Hz. Less critical than (1) but can
      contribute to GPU stalls at extremes.

Eyedropper "picked wrong color" — three causes (Apr 27):
  (1) Sampled the active layer's texture only. Color the user saw on
      another layer would come back transparent (or wrong).
  (2) Layer textures store premultiplied RGBA (per the brush fragment
      shader); reading raw bytes into UIColor produced muddy
      half-bright colors at any non-opaque pixel.
  (3) Tap on alpha-0 canvas silently set the brush to transparent
      black; subsequent strokes appeared to vanish.
  Fix: composite visible layers over white, sample that, un-premultiply
  by alpha (no-op on the composite since alpha = 1.0), bail if alpha
  < 0.01.

Color picker "couldn't pick muted colors" — single cause (Apr 27):
  AdvancedColorPicker.updateFromColor and the preset-tap handler both
  pulled hue out of the incoming color and forced saturation,
  brightness, and alpha to 1.0. Tapping black/white/gray gave you red;
  reopening the picker after picking anything muted snapped back.
  Fix: pass all four HSBA components through as-is.


